		<!-- Marginalia -->
		<marginalia hand="Italian">
			<language ident="LA">
				<position place="head" book_orientation="0">
					<marginalia_text>
						Achillis furore experrectus Alexander, non potuit
						dormire. Ca[e]sarem excitauit Alexander: Julianu[m]
					</marginalia_text>
					<person name="Alexander the Great"/>
					<person name="Achilles"/>
					<person name="Julius Caesar"/>
					<person name="Julian"/>
				</position>
				<position place="left_margin" book_orientation="0">
					<marginalia_text>
						Ca[e]sar.
						Nescia virtus Stare loco:
						solusq[ue] pudor, non vincere cunctos.
						Sherlij
					</marginalia_text>
					<person name="Anthony Shirley"/>
					<X-ref person="Lucan" book_title="Pharsalia" language="LA" text="Nescia virtus stare loco, solusque pudor non vincere"/>
				</position>
				<position place="intext" book_orientation="0">
					<marginalia_text>
						magnifica[e] iam Legationes non Sinu[n]t Ergophilu[m]
						dormire. Vnicus mundi Neopragmaticus.
					</marginalia_text>
					<person name="Ergophilus"/> <!-- CG: I'm wondering if this is a new name/character for Harvey or a historical person? --> <!--JG: I assume the former (based on Harvey's characterization of Ergophilus)-->
				</position>
			</language>
			<translation>
				Roused by the fury of Achilles, Alexander was unable to sleep.
				Alexander excited Caesar, and Caesar Julian.
				'His virtue not knowing how to stand in one place,
				and his one disgrace, was not to conquer' those joined together.
				Now, the magnificent ambassadors of Shirley won't let Ergophilus sleep.
				The sole new pragmatic man in the world.
			</translation>
		</marginalia>
		
		<marginalia hand="Italian">
			<language ident="LA">
				<position place="intext" book_orientation="0">
					<marginalia_text>
						Cert&egrave; Arma, virumq[ue] scit: Arma, sophumq[ue] non scit.
					</marginalia_text>
					<X-ref person="Virgil" book_title="Aeneid" language="LA" text="Arma, virumq[ue]"/>
				</position>
				<position place="left_margin" book_orientation="0">
					<marginalia_text>
						Et subit&ograve; deficiet,
						non satis
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
				<position place="intext" book_orientation="0">
					<marginalia_text>
						Polytechnus, Politicus, mundi peritus.
						Plus habet Alexandri, qu&agrave;m Ca[e]saris. Aut Ca[e]sar est
					</marginalia_text>
					<person name="Alexander the Great"/>
					<person name="Julius Caesar"/>
				</position>
				<position place="left_margin" book_orientation="0">
					<marginalia_text>
						Sine dictatura, vel imperio: ideoq[ue]
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
				<position place="tail" book_orientation="0">
					<marginalia_text>
						Maiori indiget artiu[m], professionu[m], arcanoru[m] facultate.
						Nouo viro nullus satis est animi, corporis, fortuna[e] valor.
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
			</language>
			<translation>
				Clearly he knows 'arms and the man,' but he doesn't know 'arms and the wise man.'
				And he will immediately fail, as he is not poly-technical, political, or experienced enough in the world.
				He has more of Alexander than of Caesar. Else Caesar is without a dictatorship or empire, and for that reason,
				he needs a greater ability in the arts, professions, or mysteries.
				For the new man, no valor of mind, body, and fortune is enough.
			</translation>
		</marginalia>
		
		<marginalia hand="Italian" marginalia_continues_from="Ha2.141r_0001" book_id="FolgersHa2" marginalia_from_transcription="Ha2.141r.xml" id="Ha2.140v_0001">
			<language ident="LA">
				<position place="right_margin" book_orientation="270">
					<marginalia_text>
						<!-- Continued from facing page, left margin, Ha2.141r --> [[G5r]: Ille noster in dicendo, agendoq[ue] grauiss[im]a semper expeditus,
						et laetus: etiam in Tragic&ugrave;s Co[micus]. Totus mu[n]dus no[n] dignus tristi =]
						= vultu: nedum Corde ferenti a[e]gr&egrave;, id est, sordid&egrave;, et miser&egrave;.
						Nam vulgares isti, pla[e]runq[ue] ignobiles, sordidi, miserabil[e]s.
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
				<position place="intext" book_orientation="270">
					<marginalia_text>
						At Ille in a[e]rumnosissimis
						negociationibus
						semper festiuissimus.
					</marginalia_text>
					<emphasis method="pen" type="straight" text="festiuissimus."/>
				</position>
			</language>
			<translation>
				[[G5r]: Our man there is most ready and cheerful in saying and doing the most serious things;
				even in a tragedy, he is comic. The entire world is not worthy of a sad] face: still less hardly of bearing a heart; that is, in a foul and wretched manner.
				For those men are vulgar, and many of them are ignoble, foul, and wretched.
				But He remains ever lively, even while most afflicted by troubles.
			</translation>
		</marginalia>		
		
